1 (7) "Practice of audiology":
2 (a) Means to:
3 1. Evaluate, diagnose, manage, and treat auditory or vestibular
4 conditions in the human ear;
5 2. Prescribe, order, sell, dispense, or fit hearing aids to an individual for
6 the correction or relief of a condition for which hearing aids are
7 worn;
8 3. Prescribe, order, sell, dispense, or externally fit a sound processor to
9 an osseo-integrated device for the correction or relief of a condition
10 for which osseo-integrated devices are worn; and
11 4. Prescribe, order, sell, dispense, or externally fit a sound processor to a
12 cochlear implant for the correction or relief of a condition for which
13 cochlear implants are worn;
14 (b) Includes:
15 1. Conducting health screenings;
16 2. Removing a foreign body from the external auditory canal that is not
17 impacted to the point it requires anesthesia;
18 3. Removing cerumen from the external auditory canal that is not
19 impacted to the point it requires anesthesia;
20 4. Ordering cultures and bloodwork testing as it relates to the auditory or
21 vestibular conditions of the human ear;
22 5. Ordering and performing in-office, non-radiographic scanning or
23 imaging of the external auditory canal;
24 6. Ordering radiographic imaging as it relates to the auditory or
25 vestibular conditions in the human ear; and
26 7. Employing, applying, administering, and prescribing topical otologic
27 pharmaceutical agents; and
Page 2 of 5
XXXX 1/20/2026 2:59 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 900
1 (c) Does not include:
2 1. Surgery that uses an instrument, including a laser, scalpel, needle,
3 cautery, cryoprobe, or suture, in which human tissue is cut, burned,
4 vaporized, removed, or otherwise permanently altered by mechanical
5 means, laser, ionizing radiation, ultrasound, or other means;
6 2. Osseo-integrated device surgery;
7 3. Cochlear implant surgery;
8 4. The preparation, operation, or performance of radiographic
9 imagery[the application of principles, methods, and procedures of
10 measurement, testing, appraisal, prediction, consultation, counseling,
11 and instruction related to hearing and disorders of hearing for the
12 purpose of modifying communicative disorders involving speech,
13 language, auditory behavior, or other aberrant behavior related to
14 hearing loss; planning, directing, conducting, or participating in
15 identification and hearing conservation programs; and habilitative and
16 rehabilitative programs, including hearing aid recommendations and
17 evaluation, prescribing, ordering the use of, selling and fitting hearing
18 instruments, including the selling and fitting of both prescription
19 hearing aids and over-the-counter hearing aids, auditory training, or
20 speech reading]; or
21 5. The independent diagnosis or treatment of suspected malignancies of
22 the ear, external canal, or skull base, which shall be referred to a
23 physician licensed under KRS Chapter 311;
24 (8) "Practice of speech pathology" means the application of principles, methods, and
25 procedures for the measurement, testing, audiometric screening, identification,
26 appraisal, determination of prognosis, evaluation, consultation, remediation,
27 counseling, instruction, and research related to the development and disorders of
Page 3 of 5
XXXX 1/20/2026 2:59 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 900
1 speech, voice, verbal and written language, cognition/communication, or oral and
2 pharyngeal sensorimotor competencies for the purpose of designing and
3 implementing programs for the amelioration of these disorders and conditions. Any
4 representation to the public by title or by description of services, methods, or
5 procedures for the evaluation, counseling, remediation, consultation, measurement,
6 testing, audiometric screening, identification, appraisal, instruction, and research of
7 persons diagnosed with conditions or disorders affecting speech, voice, verbal, and
8 written language, cognition/communication, or oral and pharyngeal sensorimotor
9 competencies shall be considered to be the practice of speech-language pathology;
10 (9) "Sound processor" means a nonsurgical, external unit that attaches to an
11 internal osseo-integrated device or cochlear implant;
12 (10) "Speech-language pathologist" means one who practices speech-language
13 pathology. A speech-language pathologist may describe himself or herself to the
14 public by any title or description of services incorporating the words "speech-
15 language pathologist," "speech-language pathology," "speech-language therapy,"
16 "speech-language correction," "speech-language correctionist," "speech-language
17 therapist," "speech clinic," "speech clinician," "speech pathologist," "language
18 pathologist," "language pathology," "language therapist," "logopedics,"
19 "logopedist," "communicology," "communicologist," "aphasiologist," "voice
20 therapy," "voice therapist," "voice pathology," "voice pathologist," "phoniatrist,"
21 "communication disorders," or "verbal therapist";
22 (11)[(10)] "Speech-language pathology assistant" means one who assists in the practice
23 of speech-language pathology only under the supervision and direction of an
24 appropriately qualified supervisor and only within the public school system in the
25 Commonwealth. Any speech-language pathology services provided without
26 appropriate supervision or outside the public school system shall be deemed to be
27 the unlicensed practice of speech-language pathology and shall subject the
